  "prompt": "When the hydronium-ion concentration of a solution is 1\u00d710\u221212 M , what is the pH of the solution?",
  "response": "To find the pH of a solution, we can use the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log[\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+]\n\\]\n\nGiven that the hydronium ion concentration \\([\\text{H}_3\\text{O}^+]\\) is \\(1 \\times 10^{-12}\\) M, we can substitute this value into the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -\\log(1 \\times 10^{-12})\n\\]\n\nUsing the properties of logarithms, we have:\n\n\\[\n\\text{pH} = -(-12) = 12\n\\]\n\nThus, the pH of the solution is **12**.\n\nIt's also important to note that such a low concentration of hydronium ions typically indicates a basic solution, as the pH scale ranges from 0 to 14, where pH less than 7 is acidic, and pH greater than 7 is basic.",
